#compdef aisnode
# ============================================================================
# aisnode - NVIDIA AIStore distributed storage
#            server daemon (proxy or target role)
#            (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : NVIDIA Corporation (NVIDIA/aistore)
# Upstream: https://github.com/NVIDIA/aistore
#
# `aisnode` is the AIStore daemon - the single
# binary that runs either as a "proxy" (cluster
# coordinator + S3-compatible HTTP gateway) or a
# "target" (the storage node holding actual blob
# data on local mountpaths). AIStore is NVIDIA's
# scalable storage system designed for AI/ML
# training workloads (Petabyte-scale datasets read
# at full network bandwidth into GPU clusters).
#
# AIStore distinguishes itself from S3/MinIO/HDFS:
#   - Built-in ETL/transform-on-GET pipelines
#     (transform data as it streams to the GPU)
#   - Native PyTorch + TensorFlow dataset
#     integration
#   - Sharded-archive format for small-file
#     workloads (millions of training files per
#     bucket without filesystem-level overhead)
#   - Erasure-coded buckets via Reed-Solomon
#     (configurable N+K data+parity shards per
#     object)
#   - S3 + Google Cloud Storage + Azure Blob
#     compatibility (target acts as gateway +
#     cache to remote backends)
#
# Use cases:
#   - GPU training data warehouse (replace HDFS/
#     Ceph for AI workloads)
#   - Multi-cloud unified storage gateway (cache
#     S3/GCS/Azure data locally + serve at LAN
#     speeds)
#   - Self-hosted S3 with ML-specific features
#     (ETL/transforms, sharded archives, batch
#     reads)
#   - PyTorch DataLoader / TensorFlow tf.data
#     backend
#
# Usage:
#   aisnode -role proxy [options]
#   aisnode -role target [options]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag.FlagSet` declared in
# ais/daemon.go::initFlags); single-dash style with
# underscore_separated names:
#   -role <proxy|target>           - role of this
#                                     aisnode
#   -daemon_id <id>                - user-specified
#                                     node ID
#                                     (advanced
#                                     usage)
#   -config <path>                 - path to global
#                                     cluster
#                                     config JSON
#   -local_config <path>           - path to local
#                                     node config
#                                     JSON
#                                     (mountpaths,
#                                     ports, log
#                                     dir)
#   -config_custom <kv>            - custom config
#                                     overrides
#                                     (k1=v1,k2=v2)
#   -transient                     - do not
#                                     persist
#                                     customized
#                                     (via
#                                     -config_custom)
#                                     configuration
#                                     across
#                                     restarts
#   -standby                       - target only:
#                                     start in
#                                     standby mode
#                                     (no I/O until
#                                     primary
#                                     promotes)
#   -loopback                      - target only:
#                                     allow use of
#                                     loopback
#                                     devices for
#                                     mountpaths
#                                     (testing)
#   -start_with_lost_mountpath     - target only:
#                                     start even
#                                     if one or
#                                     more
#                                     mountpaths
#                                     are
#                                     unavailable
#                                     (degraded
#                                     mode)
#   -ntargets <n>                  - proxy only:
#                                     expected
#                                     number of
#                                     targets at
#                                     startup (used
#                                     for primary
#                                     election
#                                     timing)
#   -skip_startup                  - skip the
#                                     standard
#                                     startup
#                                     sequence
#                                     (advanced
#                                     debugging)
#   -h                             - show usage
#                                     and exit
#
# Example invocation:
#   aisnode -role proxy \
#           -config /etc/ais/global.json \
#           -local_config /etc/ais/local.json \
#           -ntargets 10
#
#   aisnode -role target \
#           -config /etc/ais/global.json \
#           -local_config /etc/ais/local.json
#
# The klauspost/reedsolomon lane is built on
# `github.com/klauspost/reedsolomon v1.13.3`
# (declared verbatim at upstream go.mod HEAD as a
# direct dep, imported as
# `"github.com/klauspost/reedsolomon"` in
# `ec/putjogger.go` line 29 + `ec/getjogger.go`),
# the canonical Go Reed-Solomon erasure coding
# library by Klaus Post - github.com/klauspost/
# reedsolomon.
#
# aisnode imports the `ec/` package via
# `github.com/NVIDIA/aistore/ais` which references
# the EC subsystem for erasure-coded bucket
# storage. When a target receives a PUT for an
# object in an EC-enabled bucket, the `ec/
# putjogger.go` path streams the object through
# `reedsolomon.NewStreamC(dataSlices,
# paritySlices, true, true)` (the Cauchy-matrix-
# based streaming encoder) + writes the resulting
# data + parity shards to the cluster's distributed
# storage layer. On GET, `ec/getjogger.go`
# reconstructs the object from any K-of-N
# surviving shards.
#
# Klaus Post's reedsolomon library distinguishing
# features:
#   - SIMD acceleration (AVX2 + AVX512 + SSSE3 on
#     x86_64; NEON on aarch64) - the SIMD code is
#     auto-generated assembly from the `_gen/`
#     directory
#   - Streaming + buffer-pool API for large-object
#     encoding without per-shard allocations
#   - Cauchy + Vandermonde matrix support for the
#     parity generation matrix
#   - LRC (Locally Repairable Codes) extension for
#     reduced reconstruction cost
#   - Hardware-accelerated GF(2^8) arithmetic via
#     PCLMULQDQ + GFNI instructions on newer x86
#   - Streaming + non-streaming APIs (the
#     non-streaming API operates on slice-of-byte-
#     slice; streaming operates on
#     io.Reader/io.Writer pairs)
#
# Klaus Post is a multi-axis canonical Go author
# joining Niemeyer + Kamardin in the Go cohort.
# His broader footprint:
#   - klauspost/compress (canonical Go compression
#     library - gzip/zstd/zlib/brotli/snappy in
#     pure Go with SIMD acceleration; depended on
#     by Caddy + MinIO + Cloudflare's Go services +
#     ~every Go HTTP server needing fast gzip)
#   - klauspost/reedsolomon (canonical Go RS; THIS
#     AXIS)
#   - klauspost/cpuid (canonical Go CPU feature
#     detection - depended on by Go ecosystem to
#     detect AVX/AVX2/AVX512/NEON at runtime)
#   - klauspost/asmfmt (asm formatting tool used
#     by the Go assembly community)
#   - klauspost/pgzip (parallel gzip - multi-core
#     gzip-compatible encoder/decoder)
#   - klauspost/readahead (async readahead
#     buffering wrapper)
#   - klauspost/dedup (deduplication library)
#
# Post's foundational role in Go differs from
# Niemeyer's (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in) - Post's
# position is in *SIMD-accelerated systems
# libraries*. Together with Sergey Kamardin
# (gobwas/glob + gobwas/ws) + Gustavo Niemeyer
# (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in/check.v1 + gopkg.in/mgo.v2)
# they form the multi-axis Go canonical author
# cohort.
#
# Post's Go RS implementation is the source for
# Darren Ldl's Rust port (rust-rse/reed-solomon-
# erasure at Axis 263 Rust slot R1487 helyim) -
# the three-step canonical lineage is:
#   Java (Backblaze, 2015) -> Go (klauspost, 2015) ->
#   Rust (darrenldl, 2016) -> all later Rust RS
#   implementations
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 263 :: Reed-Solomon erasure coding libraries
#              (forward error correction via
#              polynomial evaluation over Galois
#              fields)
# Round 1488 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 263
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : rust-rse/                  [R1487 _helyim]
#             reed-solomon-erasure
#             (Darren Ldl; Rust port of
#              Klaus Post's Go
#              implementation)
#   Go      : klauspost/reedsolomon      [R1488 THIS FILE]
#             (Klaus Post; SIMD-
#              accelerated; the source
#              for all later RS ports)
#   TS/Node : ronomon/reed-solomon       [R1489 closing]
#             (Joran Greef; pure-JS RS
#              implementation)
#
# klauspost/reedsolomon is structurally interesting
# in this axis because it's the *upstream source*
# of the cross-language family:
#   - It pre-dates the Rust port (which is a Rust
#     idiomatic rewrite of the Klaus Post Go code)
#   - It pioneered SIMD acceleration in pure-Go
#     RS code (the AVX2 + AVX512 + NEON assembly
#     was auto-generated from a Go DSL)
#   - It introduced the streaming RS encoder/
#     decoder API that the Rust port later
#     replicated
#
# The three lanes form a *port-chain-canonical*
# axis where the Go lane is the source-of-truth
# and the Rust lane is a downstream port. This
# pattern is unusual in the corpus - more commonly
# the Rust lane is the source-of-truth (e.g.
# globset at Axis 261 led the canonical
# implementation that Go + Node later replicated).
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - helyim (Rust): SeaweedFS-clone object store
#     using reed-solomon-erasure for volume-level
#     erasure coding
#   - aisnode (Go, klauspost/reedsolomon, THIS
#     FILE): NVIDIA AIStore daemon using
#     reedsolomon for bucket-level erasure coding
#     (configurable N+K data+parity per object)
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire-shard level
# - the same (n, k, GF parameters) produce
# byte-identical parity shards across all three
# lanes, enabling polyglot distributed storage
# systems where shards encoded in Go can be
# decoded in Rust or Node.
#
# NVIDIA AIStore's positioning is distinctive
# among the corpus's distributed-storage entries:
# while helyim (Axis 263 Rust) is general-
# purpose object storage and Backblaze's Java RS
# implementation powers their Vault product, AIS
# is purpose-built for AI/ML training data
# pipelines. The ETL/transform-on-GET pipeline +
# sharded-archive format reflect this
# specialization - features that general-purpose
# object stores don't typically prioritize.
# ============================================================================

_aisnode() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-role=[role of this aisnode]:role:(proxy target)' \
        '-daemon_id=[user-specified node ID (advanced)]:id:' \
        '-config=[path to global cluster config JSON]:file:_files' \
        '-local_config=[path to local node config JSON]:file:_files' \
        '-config_custom=[custom config overrides (k1=v1,k2=v2)]:overrides:' \
        '-transient[do not persist customized config across restarts]' \
        '-standby[target only: start in standby mode]' \
        '-loopback[target only: allow loopback devices for mountpaths]' \
        '-start_with_lost_mountpath[target only: start even if mountpaths unavailable]' \
        '-ntargets=[proxy only: expected target count at startup]:n:' \
        '-skip_startup[skip the standard startup sequence (debugging)]' \
        '(- *)-h[show usage and exit]'
}

_aisnode "$@"
